Topological Neuroscience and the 11-Dimensional Architecture
While the Babel Forge framework operates within a 6,400-dimensional feature space, research from the Blue Brain Project indicates that the structural connectivity of the mammalian brain supports even higher-dimensional geometric structures.3 By applying algebraic topology to digitally reconstructed brain tissue, researchers have discovered that groups of neurons form "cliques" where every neuron is connected to every other neuron in the group.3 These cliques generate precise geometric objects, and in some neural networks, structures with up to eleven dimensions have been identified.3
Simplicial Complexes and High-Dimensional Cavities
In the language of topology, a clique of two neurons represents a 1-dimensional edge, a clique of three neurons forms a 2-dimensional triangle, and a clique of four neurons forms a 3-dimensional tetrahedron.3 The progression toward eleven dimensions implies a level of organizational complexity that exceeds the capabilities of standard graph theory.3 When these high-dimensional cliques bind together, they enclose "cavities" or holes in the geometric representation.5 These cavities are of paramount importance because they represent the missing link between neural structure and function; they are the voids that guide the flow of information across the network.5

